<br>
Random, NBG, one item per person:  Random on items, if you need it, classwise, you get it before someone who doesn't, and everyone gets an item before the cycle rotates.  This is fair *for that raid*, but its not that fair in the long run.  (It gets old when you are a mage, gone on 20+ hate raids with guild, and the results being that the other guild mages end up with staffs on their first Hate raid before you.  I solved this problem by leading my own hate raids, defaulting staff to self.) I usually see this in non-raid guilds.<br>
<br>
RPP/DKP system:  Most fair -- you go to raids, you get a shot at winning stuff.  However, I've seen stuff rot (chain BP in HoT to be exact) on some RPP/DKP guild raids because nobody was permitted to loot it, due to nobody having, or willing to spend points on it.<br>
<br>
God loot:  Leader or officers pick who gets what.  This is good in some areas, where a guild needs to equip a strong raid framework for raids (making sure a MA is equipped).  This can be heavily abused though.<br>
